{"parse":{"title":"Melee (gaming)","pageid":43928848,"revid":851244117,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The term <b>melee</b> has been adopted and popularized in <a href=\"/wiki/Wargaming\" title=\"Wargaming\">wargaming</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Tabletop_game\" title=\"Tabletop game\">table top</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Video_game\" title=\"Video game\">video games</a> to encompass all forms of <a href=\"/wiki/Close_combat\" title=\"Close combat\">close combat</a>. This can include any combat that involves directly striking an opponent at ranges generally less than a few feet, especially using <a href=\"/wiki/Martial_arts\" title=\"Martial arts\">martial arts</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Melee_weapons\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Melee weapons\">melee weapons</a>. This term is especially used in comparison to other strategies, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Ranged_weapon\" title=\"Ranged weapon\">ranged combat</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Wizard_(character_class)\" title=\"Wizard (character class)\">magic</a> (where applicable) when the game offers multiple methods of combat.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#In_video_games\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">In video games</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Melee_(gaming)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The early tabletop war game, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Kriegsspiel_(wargame)\" title=\"Kriegsspiel (wargame)\">Kriegsspiel</a></i>, created in 1812, contained rules for a \"hand-fight\" or hand-to-hand combat. In some translations, this stage of the game was referred to in passing as a <i>mel\u00e9e</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/H.G._Wells\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"H.G. Wells\">H.G. Wells</a>' 1913 <i><a href=\"/wiki/Little_Wars\" title=\"Little Wars\">Little Wars</a></i> was the first to specifically outline a \"melee\" rule in his eponymous war game.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Many later wargames (and video games) can trace their origins to the rulesets first laid out in <i>Little Wars</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1968, <a href=\"/wiki/Gary_Gygax\" title=\"Gary Gygax\">Gary Gygax</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Jeff_Perren\" title=\"Jeff Perren\">Jeff Perren</a> adopted and modified the rules for <i><a href=\"/wiki/Siege_of_Bodenburg\" title=\"Siege of Bodenburg\">Siege of Bodenburg</a></i>, a medieval war game, and expanded on rules for one-on-one melee combat and specific melee weapon rules.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> This modified ruleset was published as <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chainmail_(game)\" title=\"Chainmail (game)\">Chainmail</a></i> and included a fantasy supplement which would later be known as <i><a href=\"/wiki/Dungeons_%26_Dragons\" title=\"Dungeons &amp; Dragons\">Dungeons &amp; Dragons</a></i>. The popularity of <i>Dungeons and Dragons</i>, which featured a \"melee phase\" to represent the fighting of characters outside of bows and magic, would help spread the use of \"melee\" as a phrase for other table-top and video games.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_video_games\">In video games</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Melee_(gaming)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: In video games\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>This term still applies to most role-playing games, but is often used in the context of <a href=\"/wiki/First-person_shooter\" title=\"First-person shooter\">first-person shooter</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Video_game\" title=\"Video game\">video games</a> to specify a non-ranged attack. This began with the 1992 game <i><a href=\"/wiki/Wolfenstein_3D\" title=\"Wolfenstein 3D\">Wolfenstein 3D</a></i>, which featured a <a href=\"/wiki/Knife\" title=\"Knife\">knife</a> that could be selected from the inventory, just like a gun. Because of the risk involved in using a melee weapon, they were typically the most powerful weapons available, in terms of damage. Later, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Duke_Nukem_3D\" title=\"Duke Nukem 3D\">Duke Nukem 3D</a></i> would include a button that allowed the character to kick enemies while still wielding a gun. A Nintendo franchise called <a href=\"/wiki/Super_Smash_Bros._(series)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Super Smash Bros. (series)\">Super Smash Bros.</a> had its second game released in 2001 for the <a href=\"/wiki/GameCube\" title=\"GameCube\">GameCube</a> and used the term \"melee\" in the title.\n</p><p>In strategy games, especially <a href=\"/wiki/Real-time_strategy\" title=\"Real-time strategy\">real-time strategy</a>, infantry units that do not use ranged weapons are often called melee units.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Melee_(gaming)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">W. R. Livermore (1882). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://lcweb2.loc.gov/service/gdc/scd0001/2013/20130610001am/20130610001am.pdf\"><i>\"The American Kriegsspiel\"</i></a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. Riverside Press, Cambridge. p.&#160;105. <q>The first point to be considered is the number of combatants on either side and the relative advantages under which they are fighting; the second the losses and duration of the melee</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=%22The+American+Kriegsspiel%22&amp;rft.pages=105&amp;rft.pub=Riverside+Press%2C+Cambridge&amp;rft.date=1882&amp;rft.au=W.+R.+Livermore&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Flcweb2.loc.gov%2Fservice%2Fgdc%2Fscd0001%2F2013%2F20130610001am%2F20130610001am.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMelee+%28gaming%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">H.G. Wells (1913). <i>Little Wars</i>. Frank Palmer Publishing. <q>We did at last contrive to do so&#160;; we invented what we call the melee, and our revised rules in the event of a melee will be found set out upon a later page</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Little+Wars&amp;rft.pub=Frank+Palmer+Publishing&amp;rft.date=1913&amp;rft.au=H.G.+Wells&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMelee+%28gaming%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Trevor Timpson (August 3, 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-22777029\">\"Little Wars: How HG Wells created hobby war gaming\"</a>. BBC News<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">October 6,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Little+Wars%3A+How+HG+Wells+created+hobby+war+gaming&amp;rft.pub=BBC+News&amp;rft.date=2013-08-03&amp;rft.au=Trevor+Timpson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.com%2Fnews%2Fmagazine-22777029&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMelee+%28gaming%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Luke Plunkett (September 18, 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://kotaku.com/5944058/hg-wells-practically-invented-modern-tabletop-wargaming\">\"HG Wells Practically Invented Modern Tabletop Wargaming\"</a>. Kotaku<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">October 6,</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_